<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-10-19T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-10-19T18:00:00-05:00" n="1128" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1128">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJC1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-10-19T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 19, 1916, 6 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>3497. Your 4452, 10th. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">Gerard</persName>
                            states that he received no assurances from the Berlin Foreign Office in
                            regard to the exemption of laborers, other than those made verbally that
                            no more of the civil population of Lille, Roubaix, and Tourcoing would
                            be sent to labor in the fields.</p>
                        <p>If you deem it advisable, you may informally and orally draw to the
                            attention of the Minister for Foreign Affairs the reported action of the
                            military authorities in Belgium and its alleged object, reminding him of
                            the verbal assurances above mentioned as being to some extent connected
                            with the reported situation in Belgium.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_PFL1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>